  "answer": "The critic misreads the forbidden case. The Syro-Hittite states did not preserve the Hittite imperial legitimation structure intact; they were small-scale successor kingdoms that adapted and transformed elements of Hittite royal ideology within new, localized political contexts. The target's mechanism specifically concerns the imperial structure's inability to survive the king's personal failure in battle at the head of a territorially integrated, palatial administrative system. The relocation involved fragmentation into multiple competing polities, loss of the core Anatolian heartland and its associated cultic geography, and a fundamental shift in scale and administrative complexity. That some ideological motifs and the title 'Great King' persisted in a transformed, decentralized landscape does not constitute survival of the identical ideological structure whose collapse the target explains. The mechanism accounts for the differential outcome: the imperial structure collapsed in Anatolia because its legitimation was tied to the king's personal military performance within that specific territorial and administrative framework; in Syria, the ideological elements that survived did so precisely because they were detached from that framework and re-embedded in new, more resilient local configurations. The forbidden case thus fails as a counterexample because it does not present the identical structure surviving under equivalent conditions."
